^C@2When partner opens one of a minor, responder's bidding is geared towards finding a major suit fit. When there is @E@3an intervening one level overcall, responses vary depending on what is overcalled.

Before I get into specific auctions, let me discuss the general principle behind negative doubles. Negative doubles are designed to uncover a major suit fit. Therefore, when making a negative double, responder should have at least 4 cards in the unbid major. If both majors are unbid, and opener can bid the majors at the one level, then responder should have 4 cards in both majors. So let us examine the 3 different auction types, depending on whether the overcall is 1@D, 1@H, or 1@S.

If the auction goes 1@C-1@D, responder's choices are as follows. With 4/4 in the majors (or possibly 5/4), responder should make a negative double. If responder only has one major, he should bid that major, even with only a 4 card suit. 1@C-1@D-1@H/1@S does not promise a 5 card major suit. In other words, other than the negative double, responder should make the same bid he would have absent the 1@D call.

If the auction goes 1@C/1@D-1@H, things are a bit more complicated. Since the negative double is now available, responder can take advantage of that fact. Therefore, a negative double promises exactly a 4 card spade suit. With 5 or more spades, responder bids spades. This allows your side to better judge how to compete.

If the auction goes 1@C/1@D-1@S, things are even more complicated. A 2@H bid by responder promises both a 5 card suit and 10+ points. Therefore, responder must make a negative double with 4 hearts, regardless of point count. And responder must also make a negative double with 5 hearts, if he is not strong enough to bid 2@H. That latter case also brings up another important bidding principle regarding negative doubles. If responder makes a negative double and later bids his major suit (sort of a "negative double and correct"), that shows a hand with a long suit that was not strong enough to bid the suit directly. For example, if the auction proceeds 1@C-1@S-x-P-1N-P-2@H, responder is showing 5+ hearts and less than 10 points.

